Author-Name: Joel West 
Title: Commercializing Open Science: Deep Space Communications as the Lead Market for Shannon Theory, 1960-73 
Abstract:
 Recent research on the commercialization of scientific discoveries has
 emphasized the use of formal intellectual property rights (notably
 patents) as a mechanism for aligning the academic and entrepreneurial
 incentives for commercialization. Without such explicit intellectual
 property rights and licensing, how is such open science commercialized?
 This paper examines the commercialization of Claude Shannon's theory of
 communications, developed at and freely disseminated by Bell Telephone
 Laboratories. It analyses the first 25 years of Shannon theory, the role
 of MIT in developing and extending that theory, and the importance of deep
 space communications as the initial market for commercialization. It
 contrasts the early paths of two MIT-related spinoffs that pursued this
 opportunity, including key technical and business trajectories driven by
 information theory. Based on this evidence, the paper provides
 observations about commercializing open science, particularly for
 engineering-related fields. Copyright (c) Blackwell Publishing Ltd 2008. 
