Author-Name: Daniel W. Greening 
Title: Do Managers and Strategies Matter? A Study In Crisis 
Abstract:
 Highly interactive, tightly coupled, high-risk technological systems have
 introduced the potential for catastrophic events. Although many people
 consider crises and disasters to be inevitable, our results suggest that
 firms that are better able to avoid crisis events have top-management
 teams with a higher level of functional team heterogeneity, higher
 education levels, shorter organizational tenures, and more tenure
 heterogeneity. These characteristics serve as proxies for deeper
 underlying cognitive processes such as more complex thinking, quality
 decision making, dialectical inquiry, and multiple perspectives in solving
 potential catastrophic problems. These cognitive and social processes
 appear to be successful in addressing interactive complexity in high-risk
 technologies, and may be associated with fewer faulty assumptions about
 firms' vulnerability to crises. In addition, firms whose top managers'
 time and energy is devoted to managing acquisition and divestment
 activities are more likely to experience crisis events. Highly diversified
 firms emphasizing financial and bureaucratic controls appear to develop
 threat-rigidities, a lack of firm specific knowledge, and decreased
 information processing capabilities making them increasingly vulnerable to
 systemic crisis events. Copyright 1996 Basil Blackwell Ltd. 
