Title: Health Among Leaders: Positive and Negative Affect, Engagement and Burnout, Forgiveness and Revenge 
Abstract:
 The health of an organization's leader has profound implications not only
 for the leader, but also for the organization itself and for its members.
 This study focused on three indicators (positive affect, engagement,
 forgiveness behaviours) of eustress, the positive stress response, and
 three indicators (negative affect, burnout, revenge behaviour) of
 distress, the negative stress response, in relation to the health of
 pastors, whose jobs closely parallel those of leaders in all types of
 organizations. Results indicated that both positive affect and revenge
 behaviour were significantly related to health. A post-hoc analysis
 indicated that work-family conflict was negatively related to revenge
 behaviour, while family-work conflict was positively related to revenge
 behaviour, and that engagement was negatively related to revenge
 behaviour. These results are discussed in terms of their implications for
 future studies of leader health, and their practical applications for
 promoting leader health while preventing distress. Copyright Blackwell Publishing Ltd 2007. 
