Title: Revisiting the Emergence of the Modern Business Enterprise: Entrepreneurship and the Singer Global Distribution System 
Abstract:
 This paper approaches the question of why entrepreneurial firms exist from
 a broad business historical perspective. It observes that the original
 development of the modern business enterprise was very strongly associated
 with entrepreneurial innovation rather than an extension of managerial
 routine. The widely-used theory of the entrepreneur as a specialist in
 judgmental decision making is applied to the particular point in time when
 entrepreneurs had to develop novel organizational designs in what Chandler
 described as the prelude to the 'managerial revolution'. The paper
 illustrates how the theory of entrepreneurship then best explains the rise
 of the modern corporation by focusing on the case study of vertical
 integration "par excellence", Singer. Copyright Blackwell Publishing Ltd 2007. 
