Author-Name: Dominic Elliott 
Author-Name: Denis Smith 
Title: Cultural Readjustment After Crisis: Regulation and Learning from Crisis Within the UK Soccer Industry 
Abstract:
 Challenging Turner's (1976, 1978) implicit assumption that cultural
 readjustment typically follows a crisis, this paper examines the evolution
 of the regulation of safety management within the UK soccer industry since
 1946. Employing a longitudinal case study approach, the industry's
 response to four crises is examined. This study explores the industry's
 response to changes in the regulatory framework, through the lens of
 Gouldner's (1954) patterns of industrial bureaucracy and institutional
 theory. The persistence of indulgent and mock patterns of behaviour,
 following a series of disasters, challenges Turner's implicit assumption.
 Although a move towards a punitive approach to regulatory behaviour
 effected some changes, there was limited evidence of cultural readjustment
 due in part to a 'mindset of invulnerability' (Wicks, 2001). This included
 the fixed belief that hooligan behaviour was the primary problem facing
 the industry. Our findings suggest that more participative forms of
 regulation encourage more effective learning from crisis because they
 challenge core organizational and individual assumptions. Copyright Blackwell Publishing Ltd 2006. 
