Title: Aspiring for, and Achieving Growth: The Moderating Role of Resources and Opportunities 
Abstract:
 In this article, we use the theory of planned behaviour to develop a model
 of small business managers' growth aspirations and the level of growth
 achieved. We empirically test this model on a large longitudinal data set
 of small firms using hierarchical regression. Consistent with previous
 findings and others' assumptions, we find that small business managers'
 aspirations to expand their business activities are positively related to
 actual growth. However, the relationship between aspirations and growth
 appears more complex than stated. It depends on the level of education and
 experience of the small business manager as well as the dynamism of the
 environment in which the business(es) operates. Education, experience and
 environmental dynamism magnify the effect that one's growth aspirations
 have on the realization of growth. Copyright 2003 Blackwell Publishing Ltd.. 
