Author-Name: Eero Vaara 
Title: Post-acquisition Integration as Sensemaking: Glimpses of Ambiguity, Confusion, Hypocrisy, and Politicization 
Abstract:
 Though many studies have examined post-acquisition integration challenges,
 they have mainly focused on rationalistic explanations for the
 difficulties encountered in post-acquisition integration. There remains
 little knowledge of how the 'irrational' features of post-acquisition
 decision-making may impede organizational integration. This study attempts
 to bridge that gap by examining post-acquisition decision-making from a
 sensemaking perspective. The paper presents an in-depth analysis of a
 merger between a large Finnish furniture manufacturer and three smaller
 Swedish furniture companies. By focusing on the sensemaking processes
 surrounding integration issues, we uncover four interrelated tendencies
 that illuminate why the frequent problem of slow progress during
 post-acquisition integration occurs: inherent ambiguity concerning
 integration issues; cultural confusion in social interaction and
 communication; organizational hypocrisy in integration decision-making;
 and the politicization of integration issues. Copyright Blackwell Publishers Ltd 2003. 
