Title: How Critical is Employee Orientation for Customer Relationship Management? Insights from a Case Study 
Abstract:
 This paper explores the interface of employee orientation and the Customer
 Relationship Management (CRM) process based on an in-depth case study of a
 leading firm in the UK automotive services sector. Employee orientation is
 embedded in the Organizational Culture (OC) of the firm and manifested
 through its key elements, notably assumptions, values, behaviours and
 artefacts. CRM consists of four organizational activities: strategic
 planning, information, value creation, and performance measurement
 sub-processes. Based on the case study evidence, the widely postulated
 link between CRM success and employee orientation is empirically supported
 and the mechanisms underlying this association elucidated. Copyright Blackwell Publishing Ltd 2007. 
