Title: Tournament Rituals, Category Dynamics, and Field Configuration: The Case of the Booker Prize 
Abstract:
 In this article we theorize the ways in which tournament rituals, in the
 form of prominent industry award ceremonies, configure organizational
 fields. We review field theory to distil four criteria to which
 field-configuring mechanisms should conform. We undertake an archival
 study of the Booker Prize for Fiction to explore how this tournament
 ritual has configured the field of contemporary English-language
 literature by championing the distinctive category of post-colonial
 fiction. Copyright (c) Blackwell Publishing Ltd 2008. 
