Title: Using Field-Configuring Events for Sense-Making: A Cognitive Network Approach 
Abstract:
 We explore the usefulness of network analytical techniques to reveal the
 structure of shared cognitions among participants at a field-configuring
 event. Using transcripts from a professional conference at a pivotal
 moment in the emergence of the Jewish lawyers group in pre-state Israel,
 we analyse the relationships of actors and topics raised at the 1944
 meeting. Our analysis demonstrates the underlying centrality of a subset
 of topics and actors that facilitated shared cognitive sense-making.
 Subsequent events are consistent with our interpretation that the revealed
 shared cognitions helped mobilize changes in the organizational field and
 its institutional logic, including growth in the Jewish legal profession
 and Jewish judges, use of Hebrew in courts, and establishment of an
 Israeli bar. Copyright (c) Blackwell Publishing Ltd 2008. 
