Author-Name: Paul Hibbert 
Title: Manifested Attitudes: Intricacies of Inter-Partner Learning in Collaboration 
Abstract:
 This article is concerned with attitudes to learning in
 inter-organizational collaboration. Basic attitudes to learning evident in
 extant research -"selfish", "sharing" and "sidelined"- are compared with
 those observed through research-oriented action research. A
 conceptualization based on a characterization of the attitudes observed in
 the research situations is produced. It models attitudes to learning in
 collaboration as bundles of varied stances relating to taking and giving
 knowledge from or to a partner, or excluding learning from the agenda
 altogether. The observations suggest that actual attitudes - which are
 evident at individual, community or organizational level - are much more
 varied than the basic attitudes and that they often include elements of
 all three -"sidelined", "selfish "and "sharing"- motivations. The model
 acknowledges differences in perceptions of attitudes, differences of
 attitudes within partner organizations as well as between them, and
 differences in partners' attitudes to each other over time. Copyright (c) Blackwell Publishing Ltd 2007. 
