Author-Name: Gerry Johnson 
Title: Guest Editors' Introduction 
Abstract:
 &emsp;This introductory paper provides a background to the origins, themes
 and papers of this Special Issue on Micro Strategy and Strategizing. Our
 overarching argument is that, while the field of strategy has
 traditionally concentrated on the macro-level of organizations, it needs
 now to attend to much more micro-level phenomena. We propose an
 activity-based view of strategy that focuses on the detailed processes and
 practices which constitute the day-to-day activities of organizational
 life and which relate to strategic outcomes. The paper develops this view
 by considering two bodies of theory, those of the resource based view and
 institutionalism; two bodies of empirical work, those on corporate
 diversification and structure; and finally the process tradition of
 strategy research. The paper identifies the benefits of the activity-based
 view and introduces some challenges for further research. It concludes by
 introducing the papers in this Special Issue. Copyright 2003 Blackwell Publishers Ltd.. 
