Title: Choosing Constraints as a Third Solution to Agency 
Abstract:
 The standard solutions to agency, incentive contracting and monitoring,
 are degraded by the frequency and the duration of the decisions affected.
 Decisions of low frequency and long duration are not effectively
 controlled by either monitoring or incentive contracting. For decisions of
 low frequency and long duration, constraining the firm's choices
 significantly reduces agency. Applying the theory, guidelines for choosing
 constraints are suggested, and propositions advanced. As one application,
 the mission statement is considered as a vehicle for embedding
 constraints. The theory is also investigated by examining existing
 recommendations for both the content and process of mission statements. Copyright Blackwell Publishing Ltd 2004. 
