Title: Managerial Technologies, Ethics and Managing 
Abstract:
 This paper engages with a key element of Legge's work: the relationship
 between the technical and the moral in the application of managerial
 technologies, and how managers manage these different layers of meaning.
 Taking business planning and performance measurement as an example of
 managerial technologies, these are analysed for the extent to which they
 allow for an engagement with an ethical position, using Legge's (1978)
 characterization of the role of managerial technologies originally
 identified in "Power, Innovation and Problem Solving in Personnel
 Management". The inter-related elements of the technical, the ethical and
 the practical are then used to explore how managers construct the meaning
 of management and their implications for Legge's more recent deontological
 and teleological ethical framework. Copyright Blackwell Publishing Ltd 2004. 
